HOUSE BILL 1626
M4 6lr3677
By: Delegate Metzgar
Introduced and read first time: February 23, 2026
Assigned to: Rules and Executive Nominations
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Agriculture – Access to Food
3 (Maryland Food Security, Access, and Equity Act)
4 FOR the purpose of establishing the Food Security Coordination Office within the
5 Department of Agriculture; requiring the Office to administer a certain program and
6 perform certain duties; requiring the Department to establish a rural–to–urban
7 produce distribution program to connect local farmers with certain communities;
8 requiring the Department to establish the Maryland Rural–to–Urban Produce
9 Financing Program to provide financial assistance to certain individuals and entities
10 to fund certain projects; requiring the Department to establish a certain grant
11 program with certain purposes; requiring the Department to support partnerships
12 between health care providers and certain organizations; authorizing the
13 Department to enter into certain contracts to develop, implement, and administer
14 certain programs; requiring the Department to publish annually a certain statewide
15 food security report; requiring the Department to adopt certain regulations on or
16 before a certain date; altering the Jane Lawton Farm–to–School Program to include
17 certain schools for eligibility under the Program; expanding the purpose of the
18 Program to include the support of school gardens and nutrition education; and
19 generally relating to food security, access, and equity.
20 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
21 Article – Agriculture
22 Section 2–106 and 10–1601
23 Annotated Code of Maryland
24 (2016 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
25 BY adding to
26 Article – Agriculture
27 Section 2–2501 through 2–2511 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 25. Maryland
28 Food Security, Access, and Equity Act”
29 Annotated Code of Maryland
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *hb1626*

2 HOUSE BILL 1626
1 (2016 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
2 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
3 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
4 Article – Agriculture
5 2–106.
6 (a) The following positions and units are included within the Department:
7 (1) The Maryland Agricultural Fair Board;
8 (2) The Chief of Weights and Measures;
9 (3) The State Chemist;
10 (4) The State Veterinarian;
11 (5) The State Board of Veterinary Medical Examiners;
12 (6) The State Soil Conservation Committee;
13 (7) The Maryland Agricultural Commission;
14 (8) The Maryland Horse Industry Board;
15 (9) The Maryland Winery and Grape Growers’ Advisory Board;
16 (10) The Seafood Marketing Advisory Commission; [and]
17 (11) The State Specialist for Value–Added Agriculture; AND
18 (12) THE FOOD SECURITY COORDINATION OFFICE.
19 (b) The Secretary shall appoint the State Chemist, State Veterinarian, State
20 Specialist for Value–Added Agriculture, and Chief of Weights and Measures.
21 (c) The Department also includes any other position or unit which is declared
22 within the Department pursuant to law.
23 SUBTITLE 25. MARYLAND FOOD SECURITY, ACCESS, AND EQUITY ACT.
24 2–2501.

HOUSE BILL 1626 3
1 IN THIS SUBTITLE, “FOOD INSECURITY” MEANS LIMITED OR UNCERTAIN
2 ACCESS TO ADEQUATE OR NUTRITIOUS FOOD.
3 2–2502.
4 THE PURPOSE OF THIS SUBTITLE IS TO STRENGTHEN THE STATE FOOD
5 SYSTEM BY EXPANDING ACCESS TO HEALTHY FOODS, SUPPORTING LOCAL FARMERS
6 BY IMPROVING FOOD DISTRIBUTION NETWORKS, AND COORDINATING STATEWIDE
7 EFFORTS TO ELIMINATE FOOD INSECURITY.
8 2–2503.
9 THE FOOD SECURITY COORDINATING OFFICE SHALL ADMINISTER THIS
10 SUBTITLE AND:
11 (1) COORDINATE STATEWIDE FOOD ACCESS INITIATIVES;
12 (2) SUPPORT PARTNERSHIPS BETWEEN LOCAL FARMERS, FOOD
13 DISTRIBUTORS, AND COMMUNITY ORGANIZATIONS;
14 (3) MAINTAIN A STATEWIDE DATA DASHBOARD ON FOOD ACCESS AND
15 FOOD INSECURITY; AND
16 (4) PROVIDE TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO LOCAL JURISDICTIONS TO
17 ELIMINATE FOOD INSECURITY.
18 2–2504.
19 THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ESTABLISH A RURAL–TO–URBAN PRODUCE
20 DISTRIBUTION PROGRAM TO CONNECT LOCAL FARMERS WITH URBAN AND
21 SUBURBAN COMMUNITIES EXPERIENCING FOOD INSECURITY BY:
22 (1) CREATING FOOD AGGREGATION AND DISTRIBUTION HUBS;
23 (2) SUPPORTING THE TRANSPORTATION OF FOOD FROM LOCAL
24 FARMERS TO URBAN AND SUBURBAN COMMUNITIES;
25 (3) IMPROVING THE INFRASTRUCTURE IN THE STATE FOR THE FOOD
26 COLD CHAIN; AND
27 (4) ESTABLISHING PARTNERSHIPS BETWEEN LOCAL FARMERS, FOOD
28 BANKS, SCHOOLS, AND COMMUNITY MARKETS.

4 HOUSE BILL 1626
1 2–2505.
2 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
3 INDICATED.
4 (2) “FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE” INCLUDES GRANTS, LOW– OR
5 NO–INTEREST LOANS, OR OTHER ASSISTANCE THE DEPARTMENT DETERMINES TO
6 BE NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THIS SECTION.
7 (3) “PROJECT” MEANS:
8 (I) COLD CHAIN FACILITIES;
9 (II) TRANSPORTATION FLEETS AND LOGISTICS SYSTEMS;
10 (III) RURAL AGGREGATION HUBS;
11 (IV) URBAN AND SUBURBAN DISTRIBUTION CENTERS; AND
12 (V) TECHNOLOGY PLATFORMS FOR ROUTING, TRACKING, AND
13 INVENTORY CONTROL.
14 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ESTABLISH THE MARYLAND
15 RURAL–TO–URBAN PRODUCE FINANCING PROGRAM TO FUND PROJECTS THAT
16 STABILIZE AND EXPAND THE MOVEMENT OF MARYLAND–GROWN PRODUCE TO
17 URBAN AND SUBURBAN COMMUNITIES WITH FOOD INSECURITY.
18 (C) THE MARYLAND RURAL–TO–URBAN PRODUCE FINANCING PROGRAM
19 SHALL:
20 (1) PROVIDE LOW– OR NO–INTEREST, PERFORMANCE–BASED
21 FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE TO SUPPORT PROJECTS THAT IMPACT THE AGGREGATION,
22 TRANSPORTATION, AND DISTRIBUTION OF PRODUCE GROWN IN THE STATE;
23 (2) REDUCE FINANCIAL BARRIERS THAT MAY LIMIT THE ABILITY OF
24 SMALL AND MID–SIZED FARMERS TO PARTICIPATE IN THE RURAL–TO–URBAN AND
25 SUBURBAN FOOD DISTRIBUTION NETWORKS;
26 (3) STRENGTHEN THE STATE’S LOCAL FOOD ECONOMY BY
27 IMPROVING ACCESS TO FRESH, NUTRITIOUS FOOD IN COMMUNITIES THAT ARE FOOD
28 INSECURE; AND

HOUSE BILL 1626 5
1 (4) PROVIDE LONG–TERM AND SELF–SUSTAINING INFRASTRUCTURE
2 THAT SUPPORTS ACCESS TO MARYLAND–GROWN PRODUCE.
3 (D) (1) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ESTABLISH FINANCIAL MECHANISMS,
4 INCLUDING BOND ISSUANCE, TO PROVIDE FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE TO:
5 (I) LOCAL FARMERS AND FARMING COOPERATIVES;
6 (II) NONPROFIT AND COMMUNITY–BASED ORGANIZATIONS;
7 (III) FOOD HUBS AND OTHER FOOD DISTRIBUTION NETWORKS;
8 (IV) LOCAL GOVERNMENTS; AND
9 (V) SOCIAL–ENTERPRISE ENTITIES THAT ARE ENGAGED IN
10 INCREASING ACCESS TO FOOD.
11 (2) TO RECEIVE FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE, AN ENTITY LISTED UNDER
12 PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION SHALL:
13 (I) DEMONSTRATE A PLAN TO DELIVER MARYLAND–GROWN
14 PRODUCE TO COMMUNITIES THAT ARE FOOD INSECURE; AND
15 (II) HAVE THE CAPACITY TO MEET PERFORMANCE METRICS
16 ESTABLISHED BY THE DEPARTMENT.
17 (E) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL:
18 (1) ESTABLISH PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS, INCLUDING THOSE
19 RELATED TO INCREASING ACCESS TO FOOD; AND
20 (2) PRIORITIZE THE PROVISION OF FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE TO
21 PROJECTS THAT WILL DIRECTLY INCREASE THE AVAILABILITY OF PRODUCE TO
22 COMMUNITIES THAT ARE FOOD INSECURE.
23 (F) THE DEPARTMENT MAY ENTER INTO CONTRACTS WITH LOCAL
24 FARMERS, FARMING COOPERATIVES, FOOD DISTRIBUTORS, AND OTHER
25 ORGANIZATIONS AS NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THIS SECTION.
26 2–2506.
27 (A) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ESTABLISH A GRANT PROGRAM TO PROVIDE
28 GRANTS TO ORGANIZATIONS TO:

6 HOUSE BILL 1626
1 (1) EXPAND COMMUNITY AND MOBILE MARKETS;
2 (2) SUPPORT URBAN AGRICULTURE AND COMMUNITY GARDENS; AND
3 (3) INCREASE ACCESS TO CULTURALLY RELEVANT FOODS.
4 (B) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ESTABLISH:
5 (1) GRANT APPLICATION PROCEDURES;
6 (2) GRANT AWARD CRITERIA; AND
7 (3) GRANT AMOUNTS.
8 (C) ON OR BEFORE SEPTEMBER 1 EACH YEAR, RECIPIENTS OF GRANTS IN
9 THE PREVIOUS FISCAL YEAR SHALL REPORT TO THE DEPARTMENT ON THE
10 OUTCOMES OF THE GRANTS AND THEIR IMPACT ON THE RECIPIENTS’ COMMUNITIES.
11 2–2507.
12 (A) THE DEPARTMENT SHALL SUPPORT PARTNERSHIPS BETWEEN HEALTH
13 CARE PROVIDERS AND ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROMOTE ACCESS TO FOOD THROUGH
14 PRODUCE PRESCRIPTION PROGRAMS, MEDICALLY TAILORED GROCERIES, AND
15 NUTRITION EDUCATION.
16 (B) HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS THAT PARTICIPATE IN A PARTNERSHIP
17 SHALL TRACK PATIENT HEALTH OUTCOMES AND REPORT THE OUTCOMES TO THE
18 DEPARTMENT.
19 2–2508.
20 (A) THE DEPARTMENT MAY ENTER INTO CONTRACTS WITH THIRD PARTIES
21 TO DEVELOP, IMPLEMENT, AND ADMINISTER THE PROVISIONS OF THIS SUBTITLE,
22 INCLUDING:
23 (1) PROGRAM DESIGN AND OPERATIONAL PLANNING;
24 (2) TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPMENT AND DATA SYSTEMS;
25 (3) DISTRIBUTION AND COORDINATION LOGISTICS; AND
26 (4) EVALUATION AND REPORTING FUNCTIONS.

HOUSE BILL 1626 7
1 (B) A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTED UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL:
2 (1) HAVE DEMONSTRATED EXPERTISE IN FOOD SYSTEMS, LOGISTICS,
3 AGRICULTURE, OR PROGRAM ADMINISTRATION;
4 (2) COMPLY WITH STATE PROCUREMENT LAWS UNDER DIVISION II
5 OF THE STATE FINANCE AND PROCUREMENT ARTICLE; AND
6 (3) HAVE THE CAPABILITY TO MEET PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS
7 AND REPORTING REQUIREMENTS ESTABLISHED BY THE DEPARTMENT.
8 (C) THE DEPARTMENT MAY AUDIT A THIRD PARTY AWARDED A CONTRACT
9 UNDER THIS SECTION.
10 2–2509.
11 THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PUBLISH ANNUALLY ON ITS WEBSITE A STATEWIDE
12 FOOD SECURITY REPORT THAT INCLUDES:
13 (1) RATES OF FOOD INSECURITY IN EACH COUNTY;
14 (2) PARTICIPATION RATES FOR PROGRAMS ESTABLISHED UNDER
15 THIS SUBTITLE;
16 (3) METRICS FOR THE DISTRIBUTION OF FOOD AND OTHER
17 RESOURCES UNDER THIS SUBTITLE; AND
18 (4) THE IMPACT OF THIS SUBTITLE ON LOCAL FARMERS.
19 2–2510.
20 ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL ADOPT
21 REGULATIONS NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THIS SUBTITLE.
22 2–2511.
23 THIS SUBTITLE SHALL BE REFERRED TO AS THE MARYLAND FOOD SECURITY,
24 ACCESS, AND EQUITY ACT.
25 10–1601.
26 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.

8 HOUSE BILL 1626
1 (2) “Farm product” means any agricultural, horticultural, vegetable, fruit
2 product, whether raw, canned, frozen, dried, pickled, or otherwise processed, livestock,
3 meats, marine food products, poultry, eggs, dairy products, nuts, honey, and every edible
4 product of farm, orchard, garden, or water.
5 (3) “Program” means the Jane Lawton Farm–to–School Program.
6 (4) “SCHOOL” INCLUDES PUBLIC AND PRIVATE PREKINDERGARTEN
7 PROGRAMS, CHILD CARE FACILITIES, AND EARLY CHILDHOOD EDUCATION
8 PROGRAMS.
9 (b) There is a Jane Lawton Farm–to–School Program in the Department.
10 (c) The Program is established for the purpose of:
11 (1) Promoting the sale of farm products grown in the State to Maryland
12 schools in consultation with the State Department of Education;
13 (2) Soliciting farmers to sell their farm products to Maryland schools;
14 (3) Developing and regularly updating a database of farmers interested in
15 selling their farm products to Maryland schools, including the types and amounts of farm
16 products the farmers want to sell and the time periods in which the farmers want to sell;
17 (4) Facilitating purchases from farmers by interested Maryland schools in
18 consultation with the State Department of Education and in compliance with applicable
19 procurement requirements; [and]
20 (5) Providing outreach and guidance to farmers concerning the value of and
21 procedure for selling their farm products to interested Maryland schools; AND
22 (6) SUPPORTING SCHOOL GARDENS AND NUTRITION EDUCATION.
23 (d) (1) The Program, in partnership with the State Department of Education
24 and in consultation with school food service directors and interested farming organizations,
25 shall establish promotional events that promote State agriculture and farm products to
26 children through school meal and classroom programs.
27 (2) At least one promotional event shall:
28 (i) Last for a period of 1 week;
29 (ii) Be known as “Maryland Homegrown School Lunch Week”;
30 (iii) Promote State agriculture and farm products to children through
31 school meal and classroom programs; and

HOUSE BILL 1626 9
1 (iv) Arrange for interaction between students and farmers through
2 promotional activities that may include field trips to farms and in–school presentations by
3 farmers.
4 (e) On or before January 1 of each year, each local educational agency AND
5 SCHOOL participating in the Program shall report to the Department the types and
6 amounts of farm products purchased from farms in the State.
7 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
8 1, 2026.

